Czech discovery: a substance that also works in ́steeled ́ HIV viruses
The team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds to stop the spread of HIV viruses in the organism.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also works with viruses that are already resistant to drugs.
This fact outweighs the disadvantage that the compound does not act as strongly on common virus variants as one of the existing medicines.
The disease of AIDS cannot yet be cured.
However, patients can prolong the drug collection and prevent the proliferation of HIV viruses in the body.
However, your intake is accompanied by a whole series of side effects.
In addition, incomplete suppression of viral reproduction results in the development of so-called resistant viruses, which are no longer active.
The work of the experts of three institutes of the Academy of Sciences CR, VSCHT (Chemical-Technological University) Prague and the University of Heidelberg opens the way to deal with virus resistance.
They have demonstrated that the substances referred to as metalocarborane act on the protein substance responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
Metalocarboranes are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block virus reproduction by other means than all medicines used today, so they can overcome the resistance problem.
In their work, the scientists are able to find new 'improved' compounds, which were prepared for the virus protein based on the knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding.
The metalocarboranes have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multifaceted cages, which consist of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms and are coupled by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
Homegrown and persistent virus
HIV protease is a protein substance of the HIV virus that is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without the HIV virus division caused by HIV protease, no mature infectious virus particles would occur.
