Can Islam be French?
Pluralism and pragmatism in a secular state.
At a time when Swiss voters voted in favour of a construction ban for minarette and the concern about the alleged Islamization of Europe has spread, John Bowen, an American academic, has written a well-founded and well-considered report on whether Muslims can be integrated into one of the most declaredly secularized societies in Europe — and integrated.
Some readers will read this new book out of admiration for the author's last work: "Why the French don't love headscarves" (original title: "Why the French don't like headscarves") (2006), an elegant and intimately argumentative study of a dispute that divided the country over a period of a decade and occupied it and its effects are still perceptible today.
Bowen's latest book offers a more comprehensive and bolder spectrum.
As a good anthropologist, he wants to know not only what politicians and the media say about Islam in France, but what really happens in this area.
He has spent months in mosques, schools and institutes that now offer the 5 to 6 million Muslims in France, as Bowen calls it "Islamic Freedoms".
He is a good listener, he reflects debates between teachers and students on the questions they most worry about.
Should a Muslim marry (or both) in a mosque or a town hall?
Should young Muslims be taught about evolution and the rights of homosexuals?
Can a Muslim woman marry a non-Muslim man?
Is it permissible for a Muslim to use a interest-rate banking system to obtain a mortgage?
It is these seemingly profane matters, he claims, which make up daily life, quite unlike the political dramas that the media employ.
The author recognizes a new generation of imams, teachers and intellectuals, none of them with a well-known name, possibly with the exception of Tarik Ramadan, an Arab-Muslim scholar and academic born in Switzerland.
This new generation is trying to open the debate on how it is possible to be a good Muslim on the one hand and a good citizen in a modern secular society on the other.
You don't have all the arguments on your side.
Conservatives are suspicious of the idea of French or European Islam.
The thinkers and activists who questioned Bowen are mostly dissenting from their Salafi counterparts – supporters of purist Sunni Islam, which is linked to Saudi Arabia – who today show a small but influential presence among European Muslims.
Bowen believes that Muslim values and French secularism could be compatible.
But a convention requires giving and taking on both sides.
He questions to what extent French political decision-makers (and the intellectual elite, who so passionately guard the separation of church and state) really feel obliged to pluralism.
He suggests that Muslims may have experienced harsher treatment than Catholics, Protestants and Jews who, in turn, had to make their historical compromise with secular republicanism.
He recognizes a "enhancement of the value screws" rather than a growing pragmatism.
Can Islam be French? After reading this book one tends to say "Yes, but not yet".
