A gradual relaxation
Established in the country's constitution in 1978, China's one-child policy is likely to be the most controversial option introduced by the ruling Communist Party to date.
Couples who violate this policy have to expect enormous fines -- up to their three-year salary in some regions -- and discrimination at their workplace.
Chinese state representatives have attributed this policy to the fact that the critical burden of natural land resources could be avoided, whereas human rights representatives have condemned abuses in the enforcement of policies.
In rural areas, some officials forced pregnant women who already had a child to do so.
Many couples also had sex-selective abortions carried out, resulting in an unnaturally high male-female relationship.
In recent years, government representatives for the population have gradually weakened their attitude towards one-child policy.
In 2004, they approved more exceptions to the rule -- including city dwellers, members of ethnic minorities and cases in which both husband and wife have been single children -- and in 2007 the tone of many hard slogans was mitigated.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at the Institute for Population Research at the University of Beijing, said that government representatives have recently discussed even more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children, one of whom is a single child.
