The Cradle of the Dinosaurs
Tawa hallae looked like many other carnivorous dinosaurs: The two-meter-long and 1.50-meter-large animal ran on two powerful hind legs, had a long skull with sharp, curved teeth, short arms with sickles and a long tail.
If the species had lived a few million years later, it would have been nothing special.
But Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt from the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues in the journal Science of Thursday.
The animal lived about 215 million years ago in today's New Mexico, which was then on the equator in a dry zone of the supercontinent Pangea.
Tawa opens a new window for early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
He shows us much about the relationship, the spread and characteristics of the early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began digging on the Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
We sometimes found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, which is unprecedented for deposits from the Trias, reports team member Randall Irmis from the Utah Museum of Natural History.
Some of the bones quickly identified the researchers as a new species.
During the excavation they assembled the remains of a total of five individuals.
Fund confirms theories on Dino Early History
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt it is an extraordinary find: "Dinosaurier fossils from the trias are extremely rare, usually you will find only single fragments."
Other dinosaur experts do not necessarily share the enthusiasm.
Especially spectacular is this find not, but it confirms some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
After the current teaching, the dinosaurs first appeared some 230 million years ago.
However, many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, which is why the assignment of these ur-dinos is mostly controversial.
For example, the experts debate when the lizards split into their three main development lines: the carnivorous theropods, which later included the tyrannosaurus rex, the Velociraptor and also the birds, the four-legged sauropods and their relatives, and the plants eating Ornithischia (bird pool sour), which included, for example, the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus.
After the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa hallae is an original theropode.
He has an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, says Nesbitt.
At the skull of Tawa hallae, for example, the researchers found evidence of air sacs, such as the descendants of the theropods, the birds.
Thanks to the air sacs, the breathing of the birds is more efficient than that of the mammals.
At Tawa hallae the bones of the spine were apparently partly filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropode with air bags, says Randall Irmis.
Since the related line of the huge sauropods later also had air bags and lightweight bones, probably the common ancestor of both groups had already produced this useful innovation.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known so far lived in South America, the researchers concluded that the lizards appeared there for the first time.
Thus, the three development lines separated early and spread from South America across all continents, which at that time formed a single land mass as a supercontinent Pangäa.
For this the fact that the team together with Tawa hallae found the remains of two other, not particularly closely related theropods.
The three cannot be derived from a common immigrant ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe that there were at least three waves of migration to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, a co-author of the science study.
Of course, there are also contradictions.
An even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to a sister group of dinosaurs, lived in today's Poland, says Bonner paleontologist Martin Sander.
His opinion could be a distorted picture, because in South America just a lot of primitive Dino fossils have been preserved, while on other continents there is hardly anything to find.
As the dinosaurs managed to develop from a relatively rare sideline of the reptile tribe to the dominant agricultural vertebrates of the Middle Ages, it is still puzzling.
During the trias, the dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of today's crocodiles and the flying aura and with numerous other lizards.
Toward the end of the Trias, the dinosaurs spread around the world and developed many new species, while the relationship on the border from the Trias to the Jura died out.
Success story did not last forever
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There may have been a mass death that the dinosaurs survived by chance, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted so they could beat the competition out of the field.
At any rate, the success story did not last forever.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact of a group of animals helped to blossom, which had also developed in the Trias and since then tempted a shadowy existence: the mammals.
