The affected person can no longer separate important from unimportant, the brain can no longer filter out disturbing signals, the consciousness is flooded by impressions.
Like the dream, psychosis also opens the locks for a flood of ideas and fantasies that stem from deeper layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is subject-centered, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, Chief Physician of the General Psychiatry Clinic in Heidelberg University Hospital.
The schizophrenic is in the center of the event, everything has a meaning for him.
At the same time he becomes in a passive role, he is, like in the dream, overwhelmed by the events and cannot actively shape them.
