In contrast, women are moving with a fixed position, especially in the public sector, the establishment of a family and motherhood and therefore have fewer children.
"The women of the age group aged between 35 and 49 with a fixed employment receive on average their first child only 3.7 years after the contraction, a figure which increases to 4.1 years for women with fixed employment who have taken longer to achieve this and who have contracted and realized the first child much later.
Moreover, the type of work also has a major influence on maternity, although less than the calendar regarding the willingness to conceive," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor to be taken into account at the age of women in marriage and the first child.
