Support for brake manoeuvres in critical situations is now mandatory
As with the ABS anti-lock braking system at the time, and as with the ESP stability control system at the moment, the emergency braking systems must become mandatory in European cars.
In fact, they are already mandatory for all newly registered passenger cars and light small vehicles, for the remaining vehicles a withdrawal period has been set by the end of February 2011.
The measure adopted by the European Union aims to improve the protection of pedestrians, but these braking systems can also help to prevent many road accidents due to their operation.
The task of the emergency brake assist is to exert more pressure on the brakes in the event of a critical brake manoeuvre which detects the system on the brake pedal on the basis of the brake force applied by the driver.
However, this system does not exert this pressure until the end.
According to an investigation commissioned by the component manufacturer for the Bosch vehicles, a third of the drivers involved in an accident did not get on the brake pedal before the collision, and half of them had not braked with full force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
By contrast, the braking aid intervenes in the braking system with maximum force and thus reduces the braking time and thus also the braking distance that a car travels during the braking process.
According to an EU study, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be prevented every year if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency brake assist.
There would be even fewer accidents - one expects that every fourth accident could be prevented by personal injury - as soon as the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
Then the vehicle is equipped with a system that detects obstacles (via radar or a camera) and warns the driver, while at the same time exerting light pressure on the brakes.
If the driver responds, the system helps him increase the pressure on the brake pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not respond to the warning and even if the collision is already inevitable, the brake assistant exerts the maximum pressure on the brakes to keep the damage as low as possible.
